{"cursor":"17316","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Enterprise architecture' (EA) is the process of translating business vision and\nstrategy into effective enterprise change by creating, communicating and\nimproving the key requirements, principles and models that describe the\nenterprise's future state and enable its evolution. [http://www.gartner.com/technology/it-glossary/enterprise-\narchitecture.jsp Definition of Enterprise Architecture, Gartner]\n\nPractitioners of EA call themselves [[enterprise architect]]s. An enterprise\narchitect is a person responsible for performing this complex analysis of\nbusiness structure and processes and is often called upon to draw conclusions\nfrom the information collected. By producing this understanding, architects are\nattempting to address the goals of Enterprise Architecture: Effectiveness,\nEfficiency, Agility, and Durability. [http://www.pragmaticea.com/display-doc.asp?DocName=peaf-\nfoundation-vision Pragmatic Enterprise Architecture Foundation, PEAF Foundation\n- Vision]\n","linknr":351,"url":"Enterprise_architecture","recorded":1362568850,"links":41,"instances":["computer_science"],"pdf":["http://www.iese.edu/en/files/6_29338.pdf","http://www.whitehouse.gov/sites/default/files/omb/assets/fea_docs/FEA_Practice_Guidance_Nov_2007.pdf","http://www.acm.org/education/curricula/IS%202010%20ACM%20final.pdf"],"categories":["Human resource management","Information science","Design","Enterprise architecture|"],"headings":["Definition","Scope","Developing an Enterprise Level Architectural Description","Using an enterprise architecture","Benefits of enterprise architecture","The growing use of enterprise architecture","Relationship to other disciplines","Published examples","Academic qualifications","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Architectural_Levels_